*PERMANOVA*
```{r}
#PERMANOVA is the standard statistical tests for compositional sequencing data. You can test if overall community structures are significantly different between sample groups. This will not say which taxa are driving these changes (we will have to use a differential abundance test for that (later)).

ps_perm <- ps %>%
  tax_transform("identity") %>%
  dist_calc("aitchison") %>%
  dist_permanova(
    variables = c("experiment_day", "medium", "pool"),
    interactions = c("experiment_day*medium"),
    n_perms = 999, # you should use more permutations in your real analyses!
    n_processes = 1
  )
ps_perm %>% perm_get()
```

*BETA DISPERSION*
```{r}
#BETA Dispersion tests are typically paired with a PERMANOVA to better clarify if any significant differences between test groups are due to differences in the average community location (a function of presence/absence and relative abundances) and/or the intra-group variation (i.e., variation between sample replicates). More simply, the BETA dispersion test will tell you if the difference in intra-group variation between two sample groupings is statistically significant. 
betadisperse<-ps %>%
  tax_transform("identity") %>%
  dist_calc("aitchison") %>%
  dist_get()

beta<-betadisper(betadisperse, group = sample_data(ps)$medium, type = "centroid")
perm_test<- permutest(beta)
print(perm_test)
```
