*Composition heatmaps*
#I find heatmaps help to highlight specific taxa that are changing the most between samples (or are the most abundant in your samples).
```{r}
#The filtering parameters can easily be tuned to better fit your samples. This code will also label samples by one variable (e.g., pool). Feel free to change this with something in your metadata (it is easiest when its a binary variable, but it does not have to be).
ps1 %>%
  tax_transform(trans = "clr", rank = "Genus") %>%
  tax_filter(min_prevalence = 0.1, min_sample_abundance = 300, use_counts = TRUE) %>%
  comp_heatmap(
    colors = heat_palette(sym = TRUE), grid_col = NA,
    tax_anno = taxAnnotation(
      Prev. = anno_tax_prev(bar_width = 0.3, size = grid::unit(1, "cm"))
    ),
    sample_side = "bottom", name = "CLR",
    sample_anno = sampleAnnotation(
      "pool" = anno_sample("pool_corrected"),
      col = list("pool" = c(
        "EXP" = "black", "CTL" = "#2BD9FE"
      ))
    )
  )
```

**Plotting taxa with statistically significant differences**
#The chosen taxa may be from one differential abundance test or by using a consensus approach across multiple techniques.
```{r}
# Taxa of interest (the taxa that were statistically significant in the ALDEX2 output)
taxa_of_interest <- c("Saitozyma", "Ganoderma", "Clavaria", "Amblyosporium")

# Filter phyloseq object to keep only these taxa
rel<-aggregate_taxa(ps2, 'Genus')
rel<-tax_transform(rel,trans="compositional") #This must come first to retain the composition of each ASV in the whole community, not just in our subset.
ps_sub <- prune_taxa(taxa_names(rel) %in% taxa_of_interest, rel)

df <- psmelt(ps_sub)

df$day_numeric <- as.numeric(gsub("//D", "", df$day_number))
df$day_numeric <- factor(df$day_numeric, levels = sort(unique(df$day_numeric)))

library(tidyr)

df_complete <- df %>%
  complete(Sample, OTU, fill = list(abundance = 0, group = first("treatment"), time = first("time"))) #Psmelt will get rid of zero, filling them in just for the plot. But note that 0 in this case can be true, or just below detection, or a sequencing error.


# Rename columns for convenience
df_complete <- df_complete %>%
  rename(
    asv = asv,             # OTU column contains ASV IDs
    abundance = abundance,
    time = time, # replace with your time variable
    group = group  # replace with your experimental group variable
  )

label_days <- levels(df_complete$time)[seq(1, length(levels(df_complete$time)), by = 5)]

ggplot(df_complete, aes(x = time, y = abundance, color = group)) +
  geom_line(aes(group = group), linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  facet_wrap(~ asv, scales = "free_y") +  # each ASV gets its own panel
  theme_bw() +
  theme(
    strip.text = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = -90, hjust = 1, vjust = 0.5)  # rotate 45 degrees
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Time (days)",
    y = "Relative abundance",
    color = "treatment"
  )
```

